\begin_layout Standard
The ECB key interest rate is increased permanently by 1 percentage point.
 This is a partial shock as foreign general equilibrium components are unchanged
, namely foreign prices and foreign demand.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is a strong negative effect on domestic stock prices in the first
 period
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
As a higher implied discount rate lowers the value of the firm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This in turn lowers the real pension wealth and the real wealth of the household
s
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The user-cost for housing increases in the long run as finance is more costly
 but is in the short run strongly affected by expected changes in future
 housing prices due to lower housing demand stemming from lower household
 income
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The economy will react as if hit by a negative demand shock to investments,
 but with a significant substitution effect away from capital.
 Thus, the negative effects on GVA and GDP will be more severe
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Scale effects in exports will set in as structural GVA is decreased.
 This will hinder crowding out in exports and increase the severity of the
 shock
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are strong negative short-run effect on the government budget due
 to large temporary drop in employment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Long-run effects on the government budget and fiscal sustainability can
 very well be positive as lower expenses due to lower wages and higher revenue
 from household and pension returns might outweigh the lower revenue from
 income taxes
\end_layout

